<TITLE> China closes unlicensed newspaper, arrests staff </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BEIJING, Nov 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Chinese police have closed an unlicensed newspaper and arrested two of its staff for allegedly reporting false news, state media said on Sunday. The Social News was not licensed for distribution in mainland China and provided false information about its registration in Hong Kong, the official Xinhua News Agency said, quoting the General Administration of Press and Publication (GAPP), the country's press watchdog. China, which keeps a firm grip over its press, has since August launched a nationwide crackdown on false news reporting, pornography, unauthorised publications and bogus journalists. Police arrested Gao Yang, 39, manager and chief correspondent of the Social News, who had only three years secondary school education before coming to Beijing to look for a job, Xinhua said. He Guiying, the paper's financial controller and `mistress' of Gao, was also arrested, the report said. The Social News had published "groundless" reports on the alleged unfair handling of a court case in northeastern China, Xinhua said, citing the People's Court Daily. Local police said Gao had taken a bribe from one party in the case for publishing stories and organised an illegal mediation outside the court, Xinhua said. Between August and October the press watchdog seized more than 30 million illegal publications and 109 people were charged with criminal offences, the official People's Daily sa
